net.sepp_tember.lib.randomizer

Class WeightedRandomizedEndlessIterator<E>

  • java.lang.Object
    • net.sepp_tember.lib.randomizer.WeightedRandomizedEndlessIterator<E>
  • Type Parameters:
    E -
    All Implemented Interfaces:
    Iterator<WeightedRandomizedList.WeightedElement<E>>

    public class WeightedRandomizedEndlessIterator<E>
extends Object
implements Iterator<WeightedRandomizedList.WeightedElement<E>>
    This iterator does iterate over elements given to the constructor in a random order with a weighted distribution. To achieve a weighted distribution the iterator has to compute the probability for each element to be returned by a call to next. So each element has to be associated with a weight, which is achieved by wrapping the elements in WeightedRandomizedList.WeightedElements.

    Instead of using this iterator directly, WeightedRandomizedList could be used, which returns an instance of this iterator when randomizedIterator is called.

    The probability for an element to be returned by each next() iterator access is calculated by the weight of the element itself and the total amount of all weights in the list. Let w be the weight of one element and s the sum of all weights in the list, then P(x)=w/s is the probability for the element to be returned by the next call to next() of the randomized iterator of this list.

    An example to demonstrate how this randomized iterator works: 

         List<WeightedElement<String>> list = new ArrayList<>();
     list.add(new WeightedElement<>(0.3, "first");
     list.add(new WeightedElement<>(0.7, "second");
     list.add(new WeightedElement<>(0.5, "third");

     Iterator<WeightedElement<String>> iterator = new WeightedRandomizedEndlessIterator<>(list);
     int numberOfDrawings = 1000;
     for (int i = 0; i < numberOfDrawings; i++) {
         WeightedElement<String> element = iterator.next();
         String value = element.getElement();
         // do something
     }
    First a list is created and some weighted elements are added. Then a randomized iterator is created with the list as source of elements. After that, an element is randomly drawn from the list by the iterator. The probability for each element to be drawn from the list is shown in the table below.
    Element Weight Probability
    "first" 0.3 0.2
    "second" 0.7 0.466
    "third" 0.5 0.333

      • hasNext

        public boolean hasNext()
        Returns always true as the iteration has always more elements. As this iterator delivers the elements with a weighted probability, it only makes sense that the sequence of elements is endless. Or else it would not be possible to create a weighted distribution of elements.
